"Alexander M.A., Bhatt U.S., Walsh J.E., Timlin M.S., Miller J.S., Scott J.D.","The atmospheric response to realistic Arctic sea ice anomalies in an AGCM during winter",2004,"Journal of Climate","17","5",,"890","905",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-1842690032&partnerID=40&md5=ee714633fe34fe3aa74937aec1d9c406","NOAA-CIRES Climate Diagnostics Ctr., Boulder, CO, United States; International Arctic Research Center, University of Alaska, Fairbanks, AK, United States; Department of Atmospheric Sciences, Univ. Illinois at Urbana-Champaign, Urbana, IL, United States; Institute of Northern Engineering, University of Alaska, Fairbanks, AK, United States","Alexander, M.A., NOAA-CIRES Climate Diagnostics Ctr., Boulder, CO, United States; Bhatt, U.S., International Arctic Research Center, University of Alaska, Fairbanks, AK, United States; Walsh, J.E., Department of Atmospheric Sciences, Univ. Illinois at Urbana-Champaign, Urbana, IL, United States; Timlin, M.S., Department of Atmospheric Sciences, Univ. Illinois at Urbana-Champaign, Urbana, IL, United States; Miller, J.S., Institute of Northern Engineering, University of Alaska, Fairbanks, AK, United States; Scott, J.D., NOAA-CIRES Climate Diagnostics Ctr., Boulder, CO, United States","The influence of realistic Arctic sea ice anomalies on the atmosphere during winter is investigated with version 3.6 of the Community Climate Model (CCM3.6). Model experiments are performed for the winters with the most (1982/83) and least (1995/96) Arctic ice coverage during 1979-99, when ice concentration estimates were available from satellites. The experiments consist of 50-member ensembles: using large ensembles proved critical to distinguish the signal from noise. The local response to ice anomalies over the subpolar seas of both the Atlantic and Pacific is robust and generally shallow with large upward surface heat fluxes (&gt;100 W m-2), near-surface warming, enhanced precipitation, and below-normal sea level pressure where sea ice receded, and the reverse where the ice expanded. The large-scale response to reduced (enhanced) ice extent to the east (west) of Greenland during 1982/83 resembles the negative phase of the Arctic Oscillation/North Atlantic Oscillation (AO/NAO) with a ridge over the poles and a trough at midlatitudes. The large-scale response was distinctly different in the Pacific, where ice extent anomalies in the Sea of Okhotsk generate a wave train that extends downstream over North America but the wave train response is greatly diminished when the model is driven by ice concentration rather than ice extent anomalies. Comparing the AGCM response to observations suggests that the feedback of the ice upon the atmospheric circulation is positive (negative) in the Pacific (Atlantic) sector. The magnitude of the wintertime response to ice extent anomalies is modest, on the order of 20 m at 500 mb. However, the 500-mb height anomalies roughly double in strength over much of the Arctic when forced by ice concetration anomalies. Furthermore, the NAO-like response increases linearly with the aerial extent of the Atlantic ice anomalies and thus could be quite large if the ice edge retreats as a result of global warming. © 2004 American Meteorological Society.",,"Earth atmosphere; Feedback; Global warming; Heat flux; Precipitation (meteorology); Satellites; Sea ice; Signal to noise ratio; Waves; Ice coverage; North Atlantic Oscillation (NAO); Climatology; air-sea interaction; atmospheric forcing; atmospheric general circulation model; ice cover; sea ice; Arctic Ocean",,,,,,"Agnew, T., Simultaneous winter sea-ice and atmospheric circulation anomaly patterns (1993) Atmos.-Ocean, 31, pp. 259-280; Bitz, C., Fyfe, J.C., Flato, G.M., Sea ice response to wind forcing from AMIP models (2002) J. Climate, 15, pp. 522-536; Cavalieri, D.J., Parkinson, C.L., On the relationship between atmospheric circulation and fluctuations in sea ice extents of the Bering and Okhotsk Seas (1987) J. 